							<div class="rowTxt">
							
							
							
								<p class="newsHead">Costs and delays will increase under proposed new Scottish Bill, warns litigation specialist</p>
								<p class="newsDate">Oct&nbsp;2009</p>
								<p><p class="MsoNormal" style="MARGIN: 0cm 0cm 0pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 150%"><span style="FONT-SIZE: 9pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 150%; FONT-FAMILY: Arial">Director of Litigation Services in <country-region w:st="on" /><place w:st="on" />Scotland</place /></country-region /> for Optima Legal, Denise Loney, said that plans to ensure all repossession actions were held in court, rather than just defended action cases, could bring higher legal costs and greater delays for lenders.</span></p><p /><p class="MsoNormal" style="MARGIN: 0cm 0cm 0pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 150%"><span style="FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; LINE-HEIGHT: 150%; FONT-FAMILY: Arial"></span><span style="FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; LINE-HEIGHT: 150%; FONT-FAMILY: Arial">“The Repo Sub Group has already had a thorough look at procedures governing repossession in <country-region w:st="on" /><place w:st="on" />Scotland</place /></country-region /> so change will be minimal,” said Denise. “But lenders will face further obligations to ensure all avenues are explored and presented to the courts before repossession action can begin.</span><span style="FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; LINE-HEIGHT: 150%; FONT-FAMILY: Arial"></span><p /><p class="MsoNormal" style="MARGIN: 0cm 0cm 0pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 150%"><span style="FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; LINE-HEIGHT: 150%; FONT-FAMILY: Arial">“Key issues raised by the Bill include allowing approved lay representation of cases, but lenders can take comfort from the fact that approval has to be by a person or body prescribed by Scottish Ministers. Lenders will also not be able to take action if the debtor is able to pay the arrears in a ‘reasonable’ length of time, but there is no clear guidance on what that means. The Bill also gives rights to the debtor’s spouse, civil partner or cohabitee to be involved in the court action.”</span><span style="FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; LINE-HEIGHT: 150%; FONT-FAMILY: Arial"></span><p /><p class="MsoNormal" style="MARGIN: 0cm 0cm 0pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 150%"><span style="FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; LINE-HEIGHT: 150%; FONT-FAMILY: Arial">The new Bill would benefit lenders through simplified procedures, however, Denise said.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>The existing Ordinary Procedure would be replaced with a Summary Application Procedure, which would considerably cut down on paperwork and plans to allow debtors to agree to shortening the two month notice period for a calling up notice, would shorten the repossession process and avoid costly court proceedings.</span></p><p /></p></p><p></p></p>
								
								
